Lecture 22 
Common Variable Transformations in Python

Learning Goals

In this lecture, we’ll learn how to apply different types of variable transformations in Python depending on the feature type. Specifically, we’ll cover:

Scaling transformations for continuous numerical values

Encoding techniques for categorical and ordinal data

Practical implementations using Scikit-learn and Pandas

Continuous Numerical Features

For continuous numerical data, scaling ensures that all features contribute equally to model training.

Common Scaling Techniques

Transformation	Purpose	Python Function
Standard Scaling	Centers data around mean 0, std 1	StandardScaler
Min-Max Scaling	Scales data to a fixed range (usually 0–1)	MinMaxScaler
Robust Scaling	Reduces impact of outliers using median and IQR	RobustScaler

Example:

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, MinMaxScaler, RobustScaler

scaler = StandardScaler()
scaled_data = scaler.fit_transform(data)

Nominal (Categorical) Features

These are unordered categories, such as “Red,” “Blue,” “Green,” or “True/False.”
We use encoding to convert them into numerical form.

Encoding Techniques

Method	When to Use	Python Function
Binary Encoding	Two unique categories	LabelBinarizer
One-Hot Encoding	Multiple unique categories	OneHotEncoder or pd.get_dummies()
Label Encoding	Simple label-to-number conversion	LabelEncoder

Example using Pandas:

import pandas as pd
pd.get_dummies(df['color'])


This converts one categorical column into multiple binary columns.

Ordinal Features

These are ordered categories, such as “Low,” “Medium,” “High.”
Here, the order matters — higher numbers represent higher ranks.

Encoding Techniques

Method	Description	Python Function
Ordinal Encoding	Assigns integers based on order	OrdinalEncoder
Dictionary Vectorization	Maps predefined numeric values	DictVectorizer

Example:

from sklearn.preprocessing import OrdinalEncoder

encoder = OrdinalEncoder(categories=[['Low', 'Medium', 'High']])
encoded_data = encoder.fit_transform(df[['rating']])

Additional Transformations

For continuous features, you can also apply transformations to linearize relationships:

Transformation	Use Case
Polynomial Transformation	Adds higher-degree terms to model non-linearity
Log Transformation	Reduces skewness and stabilizes variance
